{{about|the journalist|the human rights activist|William F. Schulz|the politician|Bill Schulz (politician)}} {{Infobox person | image = Bill Schulz.jpg | image_size = 200px | birth_name = William Dawes Schulz | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1975|8|14}} | years_active = | occupation = [[Journalist]], [[writer]], [[television personality]] }}
'''William Dawes "Bill" Schulz''' (born August 14, 1975) is an American journalist, writer, and television personality, best known for being on the [[Fox News Channel|Fox News]] late-night show ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfield]]''. Schulz is also a freelance writer and a former senior editor of ''[[Stuff Magazine]]''.<ref name=Facebook>[https://www.facebook.com/pages/Bill-Schulz/42340060035#/pages/Bill-Schulz/42340060035?v=info&viewas=0 Information on Bill Schulz retrieved on his Facebook page]</ref> Schulz is the host of "Mornin'!!! With Bill Schulz" on [[Compound Media]].
==Early life== Schulz was born William Dawes Schulz in [[Lake Forest, Illinois]]. He has two brothers, Alfred and Jonathan, and was raised Catholic.<ref name=twit>{{cite web|last1=Schulz|first1=Bill|url=https://twitter.com/BillSchulz/status/67354996496281600|website=Twitter|accessdate=29 November 2014|date=8 May 2011}}</ref> He is a descendent of [[William Dawes]], who rode with [[Paul Revere]] in the "Midnight Ride" during the [[American Revolution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://townhall.com/columnists/lisadepasquale/2012/05/07/de_pasquales_dozen_with_red_eyes_bill_schulz/page/full|title=De Pasquale's Dozen with Red Eye's Bill Schulz|publisher=townhall.com |date= 2014-05-07|accessdate=2014-10-29}}</ref> He attended high school in [[Illinois]] at [[Lake Forest Academy]], and in 1998 received a BA in Print Journalism from [[Emerson College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2273253/bio |title=IMDb page|publisher=IMDb |date= |accessdate=2013-08-21}}</ref>
==Red Eye== From its debut in 2007 until November 2013, Schulz was a regular panelist, writer, and producer on "Red Eye with Greg Gutfeld". Serving as host [[Greg Gutfeld]]'s "repulsive sidekick" who was routinely the target of Gutfeld's running gags, Schulz often looked directly into the camera (even when he was not being talked to) with his signature [[Facial expression|"crazy-eyed look]]," along with frequently [[Gesture|waving]] to the television viewing audience. Schulz provided the voice for an [[anthropomorphism]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' newspaper, named "Pinch" (a reference to [[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.]], current publisher of the ''Times'').
Schulz also provided irreverent "man-on-the-street" segments featured on ''Red Eye'', often conducted in [[Times Square]] and occasionally at special events. One included him joining the [[Occupy Wall Street]] protest on its first day and interviewing the crowd while making bizarre protests himself.<ref>[http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2011/09/24/red-eyes-bill-schulz-joins-wall-street-protest-kind-of/ Red Eye’s Bill Schulz Joins Wall Street Protest]</ref>
Schulz's final appearance on ''Red Eye'' was on November 7, 2013, and his departure (for undisclosed reasons) was officially announced on November 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaite.com/tv/foxs-red-eye-announces-the-departure-of-repulsive-sidekick-bill-schulz/ |title=Fox's Red Eye Announces the Departure of 'Repulsive Sidekick' Bill Schulz |publisher=[[Mediaite]] |date=2013-11-22 |accessdate=2013-12-09}}</ref>
==Post Red Eye== Schulz currently is the Co-Host of Mornin'!!! w/ Bill Schulz and Joanne Nosuchinsky, on the Compound Media entertainment network. Schulz also works as a freelance writer. His articles have appeared in ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'', ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', and ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>[http://www.thedailybeast.com/contributors/bill-schulz.html The Daily Beast - Bill Schulz]</ref><ref>[http://www.maxim.com/taxonomy/term/2194 Maxim.com - Bill Schulz] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114231315/http://www.maxim.com/taxonomy/term/2194 |date=November 14, 2014 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/10/travel/visiting-shawshank-sites-20-years-later.html?_r=0 Visiting ‘Shawshank’ Sites, 20 Years Later]</ref>
